snippet.title: Mastering Marionettes: Marionette Performance Techniques - FREE CHAPTER
snippet.description:
SUBSCRIBE to SWSCA on YouTube: http://bit.ly/Zp70T4
Mastering Marionettes: Marionette Performance Techniques
Buy FULL COURSE: http://bit.ly/Marionette2YTFC

Watch Obama do the splits! In this excerpt from "Mastering Marionettes Part 2 - Finish, Assembly & Performance" master puppet builder and marionette performer, Scott Land takes you through the basics of marionette performance techniques.

Scott demonstrates how to explore a puppet's movement during the build process, and then takes a puppet he has been working for years, Barack Obama, and displays the character discoveries he was able to make through fully engaging with the motion of the puppet.

FREE CHAPTER HIGHLIGHTS
- Discovering what the puppet can do
- How to let movement determine character 
- When to make adjustments for desired performance
- Considerations for costuming
- Getting comfortable with the airplane controller 

Buy FULL COURSE: http://bit.ly/Marionette2YTFC

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COURSE DESCRIPTION
Learn to do the finish work, assembly and performance of marionettes with world-renowned marionette artist and puppet builder Scott Land (Team America, The Princess Diaries 2). 

If you've ever wanted to create and operate your own Pinocchio (or stringed monster puppet), you'll learn everything you need to know in this master class on the fine art of marionette making. In Part Two of his 2-Part course series, Land teaches you the mechanical workings of the eyes and jaw, how to make joints for all body linkages, how to string your puppet, and how to build a controller, including expert tips on character performance, and more!

COURSE HIGHLIGHTS
- Tips for surface finishing 
- Mechanizing the facial features (eyes & jaw)
- Attaching legs, torso, head, hips and arms
- Creating an ergonomic controller
- Stringing your marionette
- Performance techniques

Approximate Runtime - 04:30:16

snippet.title: Amiga Longplay: It Came from the Desert
snippet.description:
A true Amiga/Cinemaware classic.

The majority of walkthroughs for this game focus on the collection of the four pieces of evidence needed, in order to convince the community of the existence of the mutant ant.

However, this longplay explores the storyline (and the conspiracies of Lizard Breath), from June 1st to June 15th 1951 (the last stand on Main Street and the final showdown with the ant queen). Thus, I don't bring any pieces of evidence to the lab.
As the story evolves based on the choices made, I've chosen what I believe makes the most interesting story. That includes letting Jackie stay at the house and revealing the pipeline scam. I also choose not to save Dr. Wells from the ants, however, I do save Elmer as I wanted to get extra fuel for the flamethrower.

The collection of evidence is available in the Speedrun recording.


(Source recorded at 50 fps.)

snippet.title: Simple Walk Cycle in Blender 2.81
snippet.description:
In this video I make a super simple walk cycle for a low poly character in Blender 2.81. Be sure to check out my previous videos about low poly modeling, armature, and rigging of this character.

The basic steps in this video consists of making 4 main pose frames and then pasting them in mirrored counterparts to form an 8 key frame walk cycle. I've kept the arms really simple and since the spine bones are not moved it's suitable for game characters where you independently want to layer mask the upper body and blend upper body animations to the characters, e.g. turning towards targets or animating weapon aiming etc.

The video assumes that you have a rigged character with armature and bones that is weight painted. See end screen recommended videos for shortcuts to my armature rigging video of the very same character.

I should also mention that this is a very basic and simple walk animation. If you have more detailed foot bones or you need more convincing movements including spine and rotational movements of hips and shoulders, please let me know in the comments below.

snippet.title: Special Effects for "War Of The Worlds" (1953)
snippet.description:
Fascinating and very informative documentary about the making of special and visual effects for one of the best and most influential motion pictures in the movie history - George Pal's "War Of The Worlds" (1953). The documentary refers to the making of innovative special effects and giving background information by providing some illuminating facts about the production. Commentaries by actress Ann Robinson (Sylvia Van Buren), special effects historian Bob Burns, assistant director Mickey Moore and amongs them, a few words from two times Academy Award Winner - visual effects designer Robert Skotak from 4-Ward Productions, Inc., who participated in creation of such modern classics and visually astonishing films as "Aliens" (1986), "The Abyss" (1989) and "Terminator 2: Judgment Day" (1991).
This cut is from the video documentary "The Sky Is Falling: Making "War Of The Worlds" (1995). 

http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0480941/

snippet.title: Forbidden Planet: The great machine
snippet.description:
this is my favorite scene from Forbidden Planet, i believe it is the best special affects scene to come out of the 1950's

the great machine filled roughly 1.2 billion square feet and had the power to transmit solid matter to any location on the planet. it was also what caused the extinction of the Krell civilization.


i'd love to see an MST3K episode about this film.
